<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Captive portals are HTTP by their nature — they live at arbitrary IPs
  on the local LAN (10.x, 172.16-31.x, 192.168.x) or on vendor cloud
  domains the captive intercepts to (n143.network-auth.com,
  splash.merakimx.com, etc.). HTTPS to those endpoints would fail TLS
  validation against an unrelated cert. Captive sign-in cannot work
  without cleartext.

  Android's network_security_config does NOT support IP-range matching
  in <domain> entries — earlier attempts to whitelist 10.0.0.0,
  172.16.0.0, and 192.168.0.0 here only matched those literal strings,
  not the CIDR ranges they suggested. Result: the config silently
  blocked every captive at any private IP, which manifested as
  net::ERR_CLEARTEXT_NOT_PERMITTED in the WebView. The user-visible
  symptom was "captive sign-in does nothing" or "cannot load" depending
  on which URL the captive flow happened to hit.

  Permitting cleartext globally is the pragmatic fix. The threat model:
  - Captive networks are inherently hostile. The user's installation of
    Gatepath is the explicit opt-in to talking to them.
  - All sensitive flows are HTTPS at the application layer (they don't
    fall back to cleartext silently — calling code is HTTPS-only).
  - The captive WebView clears cookies + WebStorage on dispose, so any
    cleartext session state is bounded to the sign-in flow.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true">
        <trust-anchors>
            <certificates src="system" />
        </trust-anchors>
    </base-config>
</network-security-config>
